Microsoft Defender for Cloud is Azure's unified security management platform. It serves two distinct roles. The first is Cloud Security Posture Management, or C-S-P-M, which continuously assesses your Azure environment, identifies misconfigurations, and gives you a prioritised list of hardening recommendations. The second is Cloud Workload Protection Platform, or C-W-P-P, which provides threat detection and behavioural analytics across specific resource types such as virtual machines, containers, databases, and storage accounts. Think of it as combining the A-W-S Security Hub for posture management with Amazon GuardDuty for threat detection into a single integrated service.

There are two tiers of C-S-P-M. Foundational C-S-P-M is free and included for all Azure subscriptions. It runs a continuous assessment against the Microsoft Cloud Security Benchmark and surfaces basic recommendations. Defender C-S-P-M is the paid tier that adds attack path analysis, a cloud security graph, agentless scanning, external attack surface management, and deeper regulatory compliance dashboards. The Defender C-S-P-M tier is where you get the most sophisticated posture capabilities.

The central metric in Defender for Cloud is the Secure Score. This is a percentage between zero and one hundred that measures how closely your environment follows security best practices. The score is calculated from security controls — logical groupings of related recommendations. Each control has a maximum score contribution, and you earn that contribution only when you remediate all recommendations within the control. Partially completing a control earns you nothing — this design encourages complete remediation rather than cherry-picking easy fixes. Secure Score helps you prioritise: controls with a high max score and a high number of unhealthy resources represent the biggest improvement opportunities.

A security recommendation is a specific, actionable finding — for example, management ports of virtual machines should be protected with just-in-time access, or storage accounts should restrict public network access. Each recommendation shows the affected resources, the potential score increase from fixing it, the severity level, and a remediation guide. Some recommendations support one-click quick fix that remediates all affected resources automatically. Others require manual steps.

Defender C-S-P-M adds attack path analysis. This feature builds a cloud security graph by combining asset relationships, network connectivity, identity permissions, and security findings. It then traverses this graph to find paths that an attacker could follow from an internet-exposed entry point to a sensitive resource such as a storage account with sensitive data or a V-M with high-privileged managed identity. Attack path analysis surfaces these end-to-end chains so you can break the most dangerous paths first rather than working through an undifferentiated list of recommendations.

Regulatory compliance in Defender for Cloud maps your security controls to the requirements of standards such as the Microsoft Cloud Security Benchmark, C-I-S Benchmarks, N-I-S-T 800-53, P-C-I D-S-S, I-S-O 27001, S-O-C 2, and H-I-P-A-A. The compliance dashboard shows which controls are passing and failing for each standard. This is useful for audit preparation — you can generate compliance reports and export evidence directly from the portal.

Now let us look at the Defender workload protection plans.

Defender for Servers is the most widely used plan. It adds the Microsoft Defender for Endpoint agent to every protected V-M, providing endpoint detection and response, vulnerability assessment using Qualys or Microsoft Defender Vulnerability Management, just-in-time V-M access, adaptive application controls, and file integrity monitoring. Plan 1 includes Defender for Endpoint integration. Plan 2 adds all the additional posture and behavioural features.

Defender for S-Q-L protects Azure S-Q-L Database, S-Q-L Managed Instance, and S-Q-L Server on virtual machines. It detects anomalous activities such as unusual access patterns, potential S-Q-L injection attempts, and access from unusual locations. It also runs vulnerability assessments and provides remediation guidance.

Defender for Storage monitors Azure Blob Storage, Azure Files, and Azure Data Lake Storage Gen 2 for threats such as access from unusual locations, anonymous access to sensitive data, activity that resembles a ransomware attack, and malware uploaded to Blob Storage using hash reputation analysis.

Defender for Containers protects A-K-S clusters. It includes Kubernetes control plane threat detection by analysing A-P-I server audit logs, node-level threat detection via the Defender agent deployed as a DaemonSet, vulnerability assessment of container images in the registry, and misconfiguration detection using the Kubernetes C-I-S Benchmark.

Defender for App Service monitors H-T-T-P traffic to App Service applications, detecting threats such as command injection attempts, dangling D-N-S records that could be used for subdomain takeover, and suspicious file downloads.

Defender for Key Vault detects unusual access patterns to Key Vault — for example, access from a T-O-R exit node, access from an unusual location, or a high volume of operations suggesting credential harvesting.

Defender for Resource Manager monitors all Azure Resource Manager operations across your subscription, detecting threats such as operations from suspicious I-P addresses, use of exploitation toolkits, lateral movement across subscriptions, and suspicious access to privileged resources.

Defender for D-N-S monitors D-N-S queries from Azure resources to detect communication with malicious domains, D-N-S tunnelling for data exfiltration, and beaconing to command-and-control infrastructure.

Defender for A-P-Is provides discovery and threat protection for A-P-Is published through Azure A-P-I Management. It detects anomalous usage patterns such as spikes in unauthenticated requests, access from unexpected geolocations, and data exfiltration through high-volume responses.

Now let us look at three important server hardening features.

Just-In-Time V-M Access solves the problem of management ports — R-D-P on port 3389 and S-S-H on port 22 — being permanently open on virtual machines. When J-I-T is enabled, Defender for Cloud locks these ports by creating a deny-all network security group rule. When a user needs to connect, they request access through the portal or A-P-I, specifying which port they need and for how long. Defender for Cloud validates their R-B-A-C permissions, creates a temporary allow rule scoped to their source I-P address for the requested duration, and automatically revokes the rule when the time expires. This eliminates the permanent attack surface of open management ports.

Adaptive Application Controls builds a machine-learning model of which applications run on each V-M by observing process execution for 30 days. It then generates allowlist recommendations — for example, allow PowerShell, allow the application executable, allow the J-V-M. You review and approve these allowlists, and Defender for Cloud uses Windows App Locker or Linux auditing frameworks to enforce them. Any process that is not on the allowlist generates a security alert.

File Integrity Monitoring watches critical operating system files, Windows registry keys, and application files for unexpected changes. It is particularly useful for detecting persistence mechanisms — attackers often modify startup scripts, scheduled tasks, or system files to maintain access.

Security alerts are the output of Defender for Cloud's threat detection. Each alert includes the affected resource, the severity level from informational to high, a description of the detected behaviour, the M-I-T-R-E A-T-T-and-C-K tactic and technique being used, recommended remediation steps, and evidence such as related log entries or network flow records. Defender for Cloud automatically correlates related alerts from multiple resources into security incidents, giving you a single investigation thread rather than dozens of individual alerts.

Workflow automation lets you trigger a Logic App in response to a security recommendation change, a Secure Score change, or a new security alert. This enables automated responses such as sending a notification to a Teams channel, creating a ServiceNow ticket, or running a remediation script via Azure Automation.

Continuous export pushes security alerts, recommendations, and Secure Score data to a Log Analytics workspace or an Event Hub. Exporting to Log Analytics lets you write K-Q-L queries and build alerts on security data. Exporting to Event Hub lets you stream data to a third-party S-I-E-M.

Azure Policy is deeply integrated with Defender for Cloud. The auto-provisioning settings in Defender for Cloud use Azure Policy to deploy agents such as the Azure Monitor Agent or the Defender for Endpoint extension to all V-Ms in scope. Security recommendations are backed by Azure Policy definitions — a non-compliant recommendation corresponds to a non-compliant Azure Policy assignment. You can also use Azure Policy to enforce that Defender plans are enabled across all subscriptions in your organisation.

Microsoft Sentinel is a separate but closely related service. Sentinel is a cloud-native S-I-E-M, which stands for Security Information and Event Management, and S-O-A-R, which stands for Security Orchestration Automated Response. While Defender for Cloud focuses on Azure workload protection and posture, Sentinel aggregates security data from across your entire organisation — Azure, on-premises, and multi-cloud — and applies A-I-driven analytics to detect sophisticated threats that span multiple systems. Sentinel uses data connectors to ingest logs: the Microsoft Defender for Cloud connector sends all Defender alerts directly to Sentinel. Analytics rules in Sentinel apply K-Q-L queries to the ingested data to surface incidents. Automation rules and Playbooks — which are Logic Apps — provide the S-O-A-R response capability. Sentinel stores its data in a Log Analytics workspace, so you can query all security data with K-Q-L alongside your operational logs.

Defender for Cloud supports multi-cloud environments. By onboarding A-W-S accounts and G-C-P projects as connected clouds, Defender for Cloud extends C-S-P-M posture assessment and most workload protection plans to non-Azure resources. A-W-S resources are represented using Azure Arc, and the same recommendations, Secure Score, and regulatory compliance views apply across all connected clouds from a single pane of glass.

To summarise. Microsoft Defender for Cloud is the central security platform for Azure, combining C-S-P-M and C-W-P-P in a single service. Use Secure Score and security controls to prioritise hardening work. Enable Defender C-S-P-M for attack path analysis to find and break the most dangerous attack chains in your environment. Enable Defender plans for the workload types you run — Servers, S-Q-L, Storage, Containers, App Service, Key Vault — to get behavioural threat detection. Enable J-I-T V-M Access to eliminate permanently open management ports. Use Adaptive Application Controls to enforce application allowlists on critical servers. Export alerts and recommendations to Log Analytics or Microsoft Sentinel for organisation-wide security analytics. Use workflow automation and Playbooks for automated incident response. And use the regulatory compliance dashboard to track your posture against the standards your organisation must meet.

In the next topic, we will look at Azure DevOps and C-I-C-D pipelines — the services that enable automated build, test, and deployment workflows for Azure applications.
